            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thanks for the suggestion!\n\n> 2022 is not that long ago, and there are likely a lot of environments where just an older version of `git` is available. (I noticed this on a Ubuntu 22.04 machine, where [only git 2.34 can be installed from official sources](https://packages.ubuntu.com/jammy-updates/git).)\n\nThree and a half years is a long time ago in terms of Git, Neovim, and Ubuntu development. The latest Git version is 2.51, which is 15 releases after 2.36. Also, the Ubuntu 22.04 is not even the latest LTS release while 24.04 contains compatible Git version.\n\nDropping the `--also-filter-submodules` for older Git versions is possible, but requires extra code that can not be (reasonably and reliably) tested and will become only more outdated as the time passes.\n\nDropping it completely is not really a good solution here given the conditions on why it should be dropped.\n\nSo unless other team members have opposite opinion, I'll close this as \"not really worth the churn\".",
