            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> If all of this hinges on dropping a single arg, then I fine I guess. But otherwise we really should not spend time on this.\n\nDropping a flag means dropping a feature (use blobless clone for submodules for smaller disk space and faster install). So the question is where the compromise should go:\n- Enable \"`vim.pack` works out of the box\" for users on default Ubuntu 22.04 who can't / won't update Git version.\n- Enable \"blobless clone for submodules\" for users of plugins with submodules (like LuaSnip).\n\nOne extra thing about removing this flag is that there is no clear guidelines/decision about when it is okay to add it again. It would be a different story if there were an official cutoff of \"this platform or OS version is not supported\". The closest thing is [`:h supported-platforms`](https://neovim.io/doc/user/support.html#supported-platforms) and it mentions \"Ubuntu 24.04\" as the tested version.\n\nI am still inclined to close this as not planned (for all reasons explained earlier; plus that this is documented). But it was not me who reopened it, so not really comfortable with closing it again.",
